<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

    <!-- When creating a new activity, make a copy of this file with appropriate name -->
        <handout margin="1in" bottom="1.25cm" xml:id="Week11Mon">
            <title>Monday Week 11 - Inverse Functions</title>
<page>
        <objectives>
          <ul>
            <li>
                <p>
                    Recall the definition of an inverse function.
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <p>
                    Find formulas for inverse functions.
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <p>
                    Check that two functions are inverses of one another.
                </p>
            </li>
          </ul>
        </objectives>
            <introduction>
                <p>
                    A topic related to composition of functions is inverse functions. Today we'll study these in some detail. 
                </p>
            </introduction>

<definition><title>Inverse Function</title>
    <statement>
        <p workspace="1.5in">
           Given a function <m>y=f(x)</m> (we can call this the "forward" function), the <term>inverse function</term> is the function <m>x = f^{-1}(y)</m> such that...
        </p>
        <em>Note:</em> It is a good practice to keep the input variable name as the output variable of the inverse and vice versa. However, sometimes we write <m>f^{-1}(x)</m> because we're in the habit of making the input variable <m>x</m>.
    </statement>
</definition>

<example>
    <statement><title>A Practical Example</title>
        <p>
            Let <m>P = f(t) = 10e^{0.02t}</m> be the population, in millions, of bacteria in a dish after <m>t</m> hours. 
        </p>
        <ol>
            <li>
                <p workspace="1.5in">
                    Find a formula for the inverse function and give its practical meaning with units.
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <p workspace="1.5in">
                    Use the inverse function to find the time when the population of bacteria is <m>13</m> million.
                </p>
            </li>
        </ol>
    </statement>

</example>

<p>
    <term>Two Key Poperties:</term>
</p>

<ol>
    <li>
        <p>
            <m>f(f^{-1}(y)) = </m><fillin characters="5" />
        </p>
        <p>
            Meaning:
        </p>
    </li>
    <li>
        <p>
            <m>f^{-1}(f(x)) = </m><fillin characters="5" />
        </p>
        <p>
            Meaning:
        </p>
    </li>
</ol>

</page>
<page>

<paragraphs>
    <title>Graphical Inversion</title>
    <p> 
    </p>
<p>
    Given the graph of <m>y = f(x)</m> below, find each of the indicated values:
</p>
<image>
<prefigure label="InverseGraph" xmlns="https://prefigure.org">
<diagram dimensions="(300,300)" margins="(100,5,100,5)">
  <definition>f(x)=x</definition>
  <definition>g(x)=x/2-1</definition>
  <definition>h(x)=x^2-1</definition>
  <coordinates bbox="(-4,-4,4,4)">
    <grid-axes xlabel="x" ylabel="y"/>
    <graph function="f" domain="(-4,-2)"/>
    <graph function="g" domain="(-2,0)"/>
    <graph function="h" domain="(0,4)"/>
    <label anchor="(2,2)" alignment="east">
      <m>f(x)</m>
    </label> 
  </coordinates>
</diagram>
</prefigure>
</image> 
<ol>
    <li>
        <p workspace=".5in">
            <m>f^{-1}(-1)</m>
        </p>
    </li>
    <li>
        <p workspace=".5in">
            <m>f^{-1}(0)</m>
        </p>
    </li>
    <li>
        <p workspace=".5in">
            <m>f^{-1}(3)</m>
        </p>
    </li>
    <li>
        <p workspace=".5in">
            <m>f^{-1}(-2)</m>
        </p>
    </li>
    <li>
        <p workspace=".5in">
            <m>f^{-1}\left(f\left(\frac{1}{2}\right)\right)</m>
        </p>
    </li>
    <li>
        <p workspace=".5in">
            <m>f(f^{-1}(-0.005))</m>
        </p>
    </li>
</ol>

</paragraphs>

</page>
<page>

<paragraphs>
    <title>Finding Inverse Functions and Checking It's Right</title>
<p>
    
</p>
<p>
    For each of the following functions, find the formula for the inverse function. Then check your work by checking that the function and the inverse you found undo one another.
</p>
<ol>
    <li>
        <p workspace="3.5in">
           <m>y = f(x) = \sqrt[3]{\frac{1}{x} -4}</m>
        </p>
    </li>
    <li>
        <p workspace="3.5in">
            <m>y = g(x) = \frac{2x+1}{3x-2}</m>
        </p>
    </li>
</ol>

</paragraphs>   



</page>

        

</handout>
